#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:87-3
msgid ""
"For complex things in GameMaker Studio 2 you would normally have an <a href="
"\"../../../../The_Asset_Editors/Objects.htm\">object</a> and create <a href="
"\"../../Asset_Management/Instances/Instances.htm\">instances</a> of that "
"object around the room. However, for graphics effects, this can be expensive "
"as every instance comes with a \"cost\" in processing due to the variables "
"it contains and the codes it has in the different events. You can reduce "
"this cost by turning to <a href=\"../../../../The_Asset_Editors/"
"Room_Properties/Layer_Properties.htm\">tilemap layers</a> and <a href=\""
"../../../../The_Asset_Editors/Room_Properties/Layer_Properties.htm\">asset "
"layers</a> for drawing your graphics needs but those are generally static "
"and cannot be changed or moved around much. However, there is one other "
"option for drawing fast yet versatile graphics effects in your games, and "
"that is to use <i>particles</i>."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:90-3
msgid ""
"<strong>Particles </strong>are graphic resources that have certain "
"properties which are defined within a <i>particle system</i>. These "
"properties cannot be manipulated directly for individual particles, but are "
"changed through the code that is used to define the individual particle and "
"the system that it belongs to. They are very useful for creating beautiful "
"and flashy effects (or subtle and discreet ones!) like explosions, decals, "
"rain, snow, star fields and debris in a game without the CPU overhead that "
"using instances has."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:93-3
msgid ""
"The basic setup for a particle system follows three steps, with the third "
"step being optional depending on how you wish to create your particle "
"effects within the room:"
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:95-5
msgid ""
"<b>Create a particle system</b>: The particle system is like a container "
"that we will use to hold our different particle types ready for use. We use "
"code to define a series of visual aspects and behaviours for our particles, "
"and then we place them in the \"container\" so that we can take them out and "
"use them whenever and wherever we need later."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:97-5
msgid ""
"<b>Create particle types</b>: Particle types are the graphic effect itself. "
"You can have many different types, each with their own range of colours, "
"alphas, sizes and movements, but its important to note that you <i>do not "
"have control over individual particles</i>. You define a series of "
"parameters and the particle will be created to have a random spread of "
"behaviours chosen from them."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:99-5
msgid ""
"<b>Create emitters</b>: Emitters are an option that can be used to burst or "
"stream particles from within very clearly defined limits. They are optional "
"because you can create particles from any instance using the <a href="
"\"Particle_Systems/part_particles_create.htm\""
"><tt>part_particles_create()</tt></a> and <a href=\"Particle_Systems"
"/part_particles_create_colour.htm\"><tt>part_particles_create_colour()</tt></"
"a> functions but they are not always adequate for every situation."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:101-3
msgid ""
"Although particles are an excellent tool for creating effects, they do come "
"with certain restrictions and good practices which need to be followed "
"unless you want your game to suffer from poor performance or even "
"potentially crash:"
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:103-5
msgid ""
"Particle systems, particles and emitters take up memory and as such you "
"should be very careful how you use them as it is very easy to cause a memory "
"leak which will slow down and eventually crash your game. One way to cope "
"with this is to have a <i>global</i> system with everything defined at the "
"start of the game and removed at the end, but if you want a dynamic system "
"then each particle and emitter (and the system itself) should be destroyed "
"the moment it is not needed."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:104-5
msgid ""
"Particles may be fast and light on the CPU, but they still require <i>some</"
"i> processing and so you shouldn't have 40,000 of them bursting across the "
"screen at a time. Limit them to those that are necessary to achieve a "
"specific effect and no more."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:106-5
msgid ""
"If you define your own particle sprite instead of using one of the 14 "
"included sprites, you should try to keep them as small as possible to "
"achieve the effect you require."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:107-5
msgid ""
"Particles do <i>not</i> interact with anything. Should you need them to have "
"any type of interaction with the user or any other instances in your game, "
"you should be looking at using instances instead as particles are purely "
"graphic."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:108-5
msgid ""
"Even though there is no technical limit to the amount of systems, emitters "
"and particles you can create in one game, you should try and limit "
"everything to the minimum number possible to keep memory use as low as "
"possible."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:109-5
msgid ""
"On mobile devices, take care with particles as <i>drawing</i> them can be "
"slow if they cover a large area of the screen (over-draw on mobile devices "
"is one of the main causes of slowdown)."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:110-5
msgid ""
"With HTML5 there is no additive blending, and unless you have WebGL enabled, "
"you cannot have colour blending either."
msgstr ""

#: GMS2-Robohelp%5CGameMaker_Language%5CGML_Reference%5CDrawing%5CParticles%5CParticles.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:112-3
msgid ""
"The easiest way of creating particles in your game with GameMaker Studio 2 "
"is to use the built-in effects mechanism. These effects are created using an "
"internal particle system which is basically a very fast method for drawing "
"graphical effects only and as such you do not have to worry about all the "
"details (like memory management) when using these functions. You simply "
"specify the type of effect, the position where it must be created, the size "
"you want it to be and finally, its colour then let GameMaker Studio 2 do all "
"the work."
msgstr ""

